---
/*
 * S01Introduction.astro — Introduction section
 *
 * Conceptual mode: generous spacing, editorial density, serif headline.
 * Primary dark background.
 * Pattern: Eyebrow → Headline → Lead → Body → UpNextTeaser
 *
 * Content sourced from: .design/sections/01-introduction.md
 */
import Section from '../components/sections/Section.astro';
import Eyebrow from '../components/content/Eyebrow.astro';
import UpNextTeaser from '../components/content/UpNextTeaser.astro';
---

<Section id="s1" label="Introduction" background="primary-dark">
  <div class="intro">
    <Eyebrow label="INTRODUCTION" />

    <h1 class="intro__headline">
      Amplifier is a framework for building AI agents.
    </h1>

    <div class="intro__lead">
      <p>
        The project calls itself an <em>agentic harness</em>. The word harness
        is precise. A climbing harness channels gravity into controlled movement.
        An electrical harness routes power where it needs to go. Amplifier does
        the same for an AI model: it wraps around the model and gives it a
        controlled way to interact with the world.
      </p>
    </div>

    <div class="intro__body">
      <p>
        An AI agent is a program that reasons about a task, takes actions,
        observes results, and decides what to do next. The model — Claude, GPT,
        Gemini, whatever ships next month — handles reasoning. Everything else,
        from tools and memory to rules and connections to the outside world,
        needs structure. Amplifier provides that structure.
      </p>

      <p>
        You already know how this works, because you've used a computer. Your
        operating system has a kernel, tiny relative to everything else. The
        kernel handles fundamentals: memory management, task scheduling,
        hardware communication. Everything else runs on top through well-defined
        interfaces.
      </p>

      <p>
        Amplifier applies this same architecture to AI agents. A small,
        unchanging core at the center handles fundamentals: loading modules,
        dispatching events, managing sessions. Everything else — which AI model
        to use, what tools the agent can access, how conversations are stored,
        what rules the agent follows — plugs in as a module from the outside.
      </p>

      <p>
        New AI model? Write a provider module. Safety rules? Add a hook module.
        Different reasoning strategy? Swap the orchestrator. The kernel stays
        unchanged. It provides infrastructure; modules provide behavior.
      </p>

      <p>
        This walkthrough covers the full architecture front-to-back. It starts
        with a map of the system, then works through each major piece. Sections
        build on each other, but each one also stands alone.
      </p>
    </div>

    <UpNextTeaser
      nextSection="Architecture Map"
      teaser="A bird's-eye view of the entire system."
    />
  </div>
</Section>

<style>
  .intro {
    display: flex;
    flex-direction: column;
    gap: var(--space-6); /* Generous conceptual spacing */
  }

  .intro__headline {
    font-family: var(--font-serif);
    font-size: var(--text-h1);
    font-weight: 600;
    line-height: var(--leading-tight);
    letter-spacing: var(--tracking-tight);
    color: var(--text-primary);
    max-width: 20ch; /* Short headline wrapping for impact */
  }

  .intro__lead {
    font-size: clamp(1.125rem, 1.2vw, 1.25rem); /* Slightly larger than body */
    line-height: var(--leading-relaxed);
    color: var(--text-body);
    max-width: 55ch;
  }

  .intro__lead em {
    font-style: italic;
    color: var(--text-primary);
  }

  .intro__body {
    display: flex;
    flex-direction: column;
    gap: var(--space-3);
    color: var(--text-body);
    max-width: 60ch;
  }

  .intro__body p {
    line-height: var(--leading-normal);
  }
</style>
